## Part 6 — Component Handling Policy

### 6.1 — V1 Approach: Observable Class as Catalog Unit

In V1, the catalog unit is the observable equipment class. The catalog does not model sub-component relationships. A fluorescent fixture is a catalog entry; its ballast type is not a separate catalog entry with a parent-child link to the fixture. A terminal unit is a catalog entry; its coil or boiler relationship is not modeled in the catalog schema.

When sub-component detail materially affects the wattage assumption for an equipment class, this is surfaced through the `component_resolution_required` flag on the catalog entry, which triggers the Enrichment Review path in the Inference Engine when component detail is absent from the session record.

This approach preserves calculation throughput at scale — the Inference Engine always has a catalog value to work with — while ensuring that high-scrutiny engagements can resolve to the appropriate level of detail through the existing Enrichment workflow.

### 6.2 — component_resolution_required Behavior

When `component_resolution_required == TRUE` on a catalog entry:

- The Inference Engine applies the class-level `w_fixture_w` for the initial calculation pass
- The observation is simultaneously flagged for Enrichment Review with a `COMPONENT_DETAIL_REQUIRED` annotation
- If component detail is provided during Enrichment, the Analyst may update the wattage assumption for that specific finding before assumption lock. The updated value is recorded in the session record with source provenance — it does not automatically update the catalog entry, though the Analyst may submit it as a new `Draft` entry if warranted
- If component detail is not resolved before assumption lock, the class-level value stands and the confidence level is surfaced in the report

### 6.3 — Future Development: Component Registry

A parent-child component registry — where equipment classes carry structured relationships to sub-components, each with their own wattage contributions and data sources — is noted as a planned future capability (Option C). This would enable the Inference Engine to traverse component graphs when detail is available, producing higher-precision calculations without requiring Enrichment Review intervention.

This capability is not in scope for V1. It requires schema extension and Inference Engine changes that are deferred pending portfolio data accumulation and engagement experience with the `component_resolution_required` trigger pattern.

