## Part 8 — Inference Engine Interface Contract

### 8.1 — What the Inference Engine Reads from the Catalog

At Stage 2, the Inference Engine reads the `catalog_version` from the session's Facilitator pre-session configuration. All catalog lookups for that session use entries at or below that version. Entries promoted after the session `catalog_version` was locked do not affect in-flight sessions.

At Stage 9, the Inference Engine reads `w_fixture_w` from the resolved catalog entry to compute `P_load`. It also reads `w_fixture_confidence` to determine guarantee pool eligibility. Entries with `w_fixture_confidence = LOW` are excluded from the guarantee savings pool regardless of other pipeline outputs.

### 8.2 — What the Inference Engine Writes to the Catalog

The Inference Engine writes to the catalog in one circumstance only: Step 3 of the wattage fallback hierarchy, when an auto-populated entry is created. All other catalog writes are performed by Analysts through the catalog maintenance process. The Inference Engine does not modify existing entries.

The Inference Engine appends to `session_refs` on each entry it applies, regardless of which fallback step produced the match.

### 8.3 — Catalog Version Locking

The `catalog_version` used for a session is locked at the Analysis Boundary Gate alongside all other session configuration. It cannot be changed after the gate locks. If a catalog entry is revised after a session's gate has locked, the session record retains the version-locked values and is not automatically recalculated. Recalculation requires a session-level escalation.

